<HEADLINE>
FT  08 AUG 94 / High achievers who 'fear only the creator': Those drawn to a
controversial Islamic group
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KHOZEM MERCHANT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
'We embrace Islam intellectually and we carry it politically. We are looking
for change,' says Abdul, a 25-year-old investment analyst with a City
merchant bank.
By day Abdul (not his real name) handles a multi-million pound portfolio for
private and institutional investors. By night he helps run Hizb-ut-Tahrir
(Liberation party), an Islamic revivalist group which advocates the
restoration of the Khilafah, a single borderless Moslem entity with one
leader, abolished by the father of modern Turkey, Kemal Attuturk, in 1924.
In the UK, Hizb-ut-Tahrir counts among its members British-born doctors,
gilts traders, computer analysts, university lecturers, accountants and
physicists. They are high achievers, outspoken and 'fear only the creator',
according to party spokesman Farrid Qassim, a former town planner now fully
absorbed with running the party.
Abdul, a physics graduate who recently completed his doctorate at London
University, is typical of the highly educated British-born Moslems whose
uncompromising articulation of their faith has set them apart from fellow
Mohammedans.
Yesterday thousands of Moslems like Abdul descended on Wembley Arena in
north London to hear speakers from Jordan, Saudi Arabia, Bosnia, Pakistan
and the US at the International Moslem Khilafah Conference. Hizb-ut-Tahrir
was one of the organisers.
Brent council, the local authority, and the Union of Jewish Students, had
urged the government to ban the meeting. They cited Hizb-ut-Tahrir's
anti-semitism as likely to inflame tensions in a multi-racial area already
on edge after last month's two bomb attacks on Jewish targets in London.
The Board of Jewish deputies expressed its concern to the government but
stopped short of calling for a ban.
Brent Islamic Forum, an umbrella group, and leading Moslem scholars opposed
moves to ban the conference, saying it would simply make Moslems more
suspicious of government motives towards the Moslem community. Any ban, they
added, would backfire in Hizb-ut-Tahrir's favour.
But Islamic scholars have nevertheless denounced Hizb-ut-Tahrir's
anti-semitic comments, carried in leaflets distributed at universities. The
party's statements about 'killing Jews' were 'wrong in theology, wrong in
ethics, and wrong in British law', said Dr Zaki Badawi, principal of the
Moslem College in London.
Hizb-ut-Tahrir insists its published comments have 'been taken out of
context', and that it is the target of an orchestrated campaign. All this
attention has raised the profile of Hizb-ut-Tahrir, which was founded in
1953 in the West Bank town of Hebron to revive the Khilafah, an aim which
led to its banning in many Middle East states. Yet its agenda - dismissed
privately by Moslem scholars as 'silly and Utopian'  - has attracted many
young Moslems in Britain.
Omar Bakri Mohammed, leader of Hizb-ut-Tahrir, says: 'We provide
intellectual leadership. This forces us to argue our case and we are
equipped to do this. This will create public awareness (for the Khilafah),
then create a public force and then public demands.' Omar Bakri was expelled
from Saudi Arabia 10 years ago and today runs an Islamic school in
Tottenham, north London.
Much of the reason for the interest created by Hizb-ut-Tahrir is attributed
to disenchantment with the internal leadership of the ummah, the Moslem
community. It is denounced for failing to address contemporary issues that
concern young Moslems.
Sohail Nakhooda, a director of Islamica, a religious journal, says that
these issues include racism, employment and drugs in the UK. Overseas issues
include the plight of Moslems in Bosnia, the occupied territories and
Algeria, and injustices in, for example, western-supported Gulf states.
This discontent has, for five years, been tapped by Hizb-ut-Tahrir.
Universities and colleges have proved the most fertile areas for
recruitment.
The Union of Jewish Students says complaints from its members about
Hizb-ut-Tahrir activities have risen sharply in the past eight months.
The party's members probably number no more than 2,000. Typical is Zulfikar,
a former futures and gilts trader with Kleinwort Benson and Merrill Lynch,
who quit the City and, after starting a physics degree at London University,
joined Hizb-ut-Tahrir. Today, London-born Zulfikar is studying Islamic
jurisprudence at Omar Bakri's Islamic school. 'What motivates me? The
intellectual pull and the desire for a Khilafah,' he says.
</TEXT>
