<HEADLINE>
FT  08 AUG 94 / Pin-striped debt collectors to pin-point Names: The growing
business of demanding money
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL CHEESERIGHT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The news that the Lloyd's insurance market has decided to employ debt
collectors to help recover funds from loss-making Names may not be quite as
alarming as it sounds. The business of collecting debts is clawing its way
up-market, and is becoming a matter of pin-stripe suits and executive cars
as much as baseball caps and grubby vans.
Lloyd's has set up a committee, with Mr Bernard Bradford as chairman, to
examine ways of collecting money. He will have no shortage of offers of help
from collection agencies scenting commission and solicitors smelling
litigation fees. The companies he is likely to select will not be at the
frayed-cuff end of the trade and will adhere to guidelines of the Credit
Services Association.
These guidelines enjoin collectors to 'be circumspect and discreet when
attempting to contact the debtor whether by telephone or by personal visit',
and 'unless instructed otherwise, to accept all reasonable offers by debtors
to pay by instalments'.
The largest operators are quoted companies such as Intrum Justitia. 'It's
becoming a professional industry with sophisticated computer systems,' says
one practitioner. But it is still possible to be a debt collector without
any qualifications. Sharks are still about.
The Credit Services Association, the trade body, has 150 members but there
are at least 300 debt collection agencies competing for business which, like
the Lloyd's debts, often springs from the 1980s.
'When credit was abundant in the late 1980s, there was a lot of debt about,'
said Mr Roy Goldsmith, association secretary. 'People were concerned about
the front end of their business. They weren't so concerned about getting
debt in. A lot of debt collection people saw this as an opportunity to make
money.'
They still do. But the competition has been made more intense with the
arrival in the market of solicitors such as Dibb Lupton Broomhead, which is
working with Lloyd's.
'It's cut-throat,' said the credit manager of one finance house. 'Every day
I have people from these 300 firms ringing up and touting for business.'
Those which win Lloyd's business will almost certainly be association
members and their executives will probably be members of the Institute of
Credit Management. Their first task will be to decide the nature of the debt
they want to collect.
Mr Terry Robinson, the chairman of Commercial Credit Consultants in
Liverpool, said: 'Credit trading can be divided into two almost at the
start: trade credit and consumer credit. Although they share a lot of common
ground, their similarities will diminish with the ageing of the debts.'
With trade debt, a collector explained, the creditor may well be dealing
with a customer to whom he or she might wish to continue selling. This would
suggest the need for a more sensitive approach than with a consumer debt
where 'all you want is the money back the fastest and cheapest way'.
Mr Bradford and his colleagues will have to decide to what extent they want
to continue a relationship with their debtors. If they decide they are not
interested then the going, for the debtors, might be rougher.
At the start, the debt collection agency will try to contact the Lloyd's
loser by letter and then telephone, Mr Robinson said.
Mr Goldsmith said: 'Basically we are debt negotiators. We try and negotiate
initially and often the debtor is more ready to negotiate with a third party
than the party who's owed the money.'
In the Lloyd's case the agency will probably be referred back to the loser's
lawyer, which opens up the whole panoply of legal process.
The trick here for the agency will be to decide whether the debtor is a
Can't Pay or a Won't Pay. If the former, then the agency will settle for a
nominal amount, if the latter, then a summons will be quickly sent.
The agency will want a judgment in the County Court or the High Court and
then if the debtor still refuses to pay, an enforcement order. This is the
stage where, as last resort, a bailiff could be sent in by the County Court,
or a sheriff by the High Court, to seize belongings.
The agency could ask the court to attach the earnings of the debtor: this
would have the effect of seizing money held in a bank account. It could
claim a property as security.
But the system does not give all the cards to the agency. Lloyd's debtors
will have the chance to extend the legal process, the longer to avoid
repayment. The finance house credit manager said: 'We've got people on our
books with three or four County Court judgments against them and we still
can't get the money out of them.'
</TEXT>
