<HEADLINE>
FT  08 AUG 94 / Experimental crop of wheat harvested
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The world's first experimental crop of genetically engineered wheat has been
harvested in Cambridgeshire.
The success of the trial, carried out by Swiss-owned Ciba Seeds, shows that
scientists can alter the characteristics of important cereals in a reliable
way by giving them genes from other species.
The work is expected to lead to new wheat varieties with increased
resistance to drought and disease, less requirement for expensive
fertilisers, and other improvements.
The wheat grown at Great Abington, Cambridgeshire, contains 'marker genes'
of no commercial significance, chosen to prove that foreign genetic material
can be passed on predictably from one generation of plants to the next.
Some of the plants contained a red pigment gene taken from wild Peruvian
maize. When they were harvested last week, all their grains showed red spots
 -looking unlike any wheat grown before.
The other plants produced bacterial enzymes which Ciba detected in simple
tests, proving that the new genes were switched on successfully.
Mr David Thompson, head of research at Ciba's cereal breeding business, said
the 16 sq m trial plot yielded several kilograms of the wheat.
</TEXT>
