<HEADLINE>
FT  08 AUG 94 / Union demands pensions payouts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Thirty-six pensions companies will today receive letters from the GMB
general union demanding compensation for alleged bad pensions advice given
to some of its members, Chris Tighe writes.
Ninety cases relating to the companies have been selected from hundreds of
calls to the union's pensions helpline, set up in May to assist members who
believe they may have been wrongly advised on opting out of company schemes
and into personal pensions.
Mr John Edmonds, the union's general secretary, has also asked the Serious
Fraud Office to investigate the cases. The SFO said it was considering the
matter.
The union says it wants each case to be thoroughly examined by the pensions
companies, and full compensation - likely, it estimates, to exceed Pounds 1m
in total - to be provided.
The union said the 'worst culprit' among its 90 cases was the Prudential
with 17.
The Prudential said it had yet to receive any evidence from the union. The
transfer of active members of company schemes to new schemes had never been
its policy, it said, adding: 'We believe we have behaved properly and well
within the regulators' rules and regulations.'
</TEXT>
