<HEADLINE>
FT  08 AUG 94 / Consumers seem cautious amid rising credit demand
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN, Economics Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Demand for consumer credit continued to rise in June although there were
growing signs of reluctance to take on heavy or longer-term commitments, say
two credit industry reports released today.
Both the Finance and Leasing Association and Infolink, a credit information
group, suggested that discussion of possible interest rate increases
deterred some borrowers.
The FLA said its members supplied consumer credit worth Pounds 1.37bn in
June, an increase of 31 per cent compared with June 1993 but up only 1 per
cent from May. While credit granted on store cards rose sharply, fewer
people took out personal loans and motor finance fell 6 per cent compared
with May.
According to the FLA's non-seasonally adjusted figures, store card
borrowings jumped 14 per cent to Pounds 415m between May and June and were
up 51 per cent on June last year. However, personal loans at Pounds 219m in
June were down 9 per cent compared with May and, although 12 per cent higher
than in June last year, recorded their lowest annual rate of increase for 18
months.
Infolink reported a strong 13.1 per cent year-on-year increase in demand for
credit in the retail sector. However, applications for credit in the new-car
sector slowed, while growth in demand for credit from finance houses was the
lowest in recent months, it said.
Mr Brian Bailey, Infolink chairman, said his company's figures provided
'anecdotal evidence that consumers were reluctant to make heavy credit
commitments in June'.
Mr David Hardisty, FLA chairman, said: 'The reluctance of consumers to take
on longer term commitments in June confirms our view that consumer
confidence remains fragile.'
The FLA, whose members provide 80 per cent of consumer credit not provided
by banks and building societies, and finance about 30 per cent of fixed
investment in plant and equipment, said business finance at Pounds 1.21bn in
June was unchanged from June 1993. Although business lending and leasing
showed a typical end-quarter increase of 24 per cent between May and June,
the second-quarter total of Pounds 3.18bn was only 1 per cent up on last
year's second-quarter total of Pounds 3.15bn.
The shake-out in manufacturing is coming to an end with companies shedding
fewer staff and closing fewer production sites, says a survey by Remploy
Manufacturing Services, a contract manufacturing company.
Its survey of more than 7,000 manufacturing sites found 20 per cent
increased their workforce in the year to June, 25 per cent reduced staff and
55 per cent reported no change in the workforce.
The survey showed that just under 4 per cent of the sites had closed in the
year to June, against 8 per cent in the previous year and 13 per cent the
year before.
</TEXT>
