<HEADLINE>
FT  08 AUG 94 / Labour attacks water profits
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ and ROBERT CORZINE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Labour party yesterday launched a new broadside against the profits made
by privatised water companies in England and Wales, in spite of recent
assurances from the industry regulator that consumer costs would be kept
within strict limits.
In a detailed attack on the activities of the 31 privatised water companies,
Mr George Howarth, shadow environment minister, said their overall profits
had risen 125 per cent since privatisation in 1989 and that the salaries of
their chairmen had risen an average 135 per cent over the same period.
He also said that about a third of the water companies' chairmen held senior
posts in other companies which were benefactors of the Conservative party,
and had donated a total of Pounds 745,000 to Tory funds in the past 15
years.
Mr Howarth said, for example, that Mr Andrew Simon, the director of Severn
Trent Water, was also a director of Laporte, the chemicals group, which has
donated Pounds 231,200 since 1979.
Mr Howarth said he was not alleging any impropriety. 'The point is that when
all these interests get so closely snuggled up together the borderline
between the various public interests, private interests and the Conservative
party itself becomes blurred,' he said.
The Gas Consumers Council has asked the government to restrict British Gas's
ability to increase prices to some of its customers before the introduction
of competition in the domestic market, Robert Corzine writes.
In a letter to Mr Tim Eggar, energy minister, the council accused British
Gas of mounting 'an intensive campaign to warn that higher gas bills, for
some, are an unavoidable prelude to competition'.
Last month British Gas said it intended to remove cross-subsidies between
the 18m household consumers of gas in a process known as 're-balancing'. It
claimed that 2m to 3m of its best customers subsidised many more millions of
consumers who either use small amounts of gas or who are problem payers.
</TEXT>
