<HEADLINE>
FT  06 AUG 94 / Independent Whitewater counsel Fiske replaced
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUREK MARTIN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Whitewater investigations were thrown into some confusion last night
when Mr Robert Fiske was replaced as independent counsel by Mr Kenneth
Starr, former solicitor general in the Republican Bush administration.
A federal appeals court panel, acting under authority granted when the
independent counsel act was renewed earlier this year, ruled it was in the
best interest of 'the appearance of independence' that a person 'not
affiliated with the incumbent administration' be appointed.
Ms Janet Reno, the attorney general, named Mr Fiske, a Republican, as
independent counsel in January to much bipartisan applause. In July, in line
with the renewed act, she recommended to the court his engagement be
continued.
The court stressed it was not impugning Mr Fiske's integrity or
independence. It made no mention of allegations aired by Republicans in
congressional hearings this week that as a lawyer, he had longstanding
professional relations with lawyers for President Bill Clinton and his
administration that amounted to a conflict of interest.
Republican discontent with Mr Fiske had centred mostly on his interim report
earlier this summer which said Mr Vincent Foster, the former White House
aide, had died by his own hand last summer.
He also cleared administration officials of any criminal violations in
discussing the case against Madison Guaranty, the bankrupt Arkansas savings
bank owned by the Clintons' partner in the Whitewater land development
scheme. Two congressional committee have spent the last 10 days grilling
officials on Madison.
It was unclear last night if the status of these findings would now be
called into question. The court order merely gave the new independent
counsel 'full power, independent authority and jurisdiction' over the
Whitewater affair. In a brief statement Mr Fiske promised full co-operation
with Mr Starr and praised Ms Reno for her support. But it seems probable the
investigations will now be stretched out. The administration had hoped the
Whitewater affair would be over by the time the 1996 election season began.
That may now be in doubt.
Mr Starr, also a former judge, is currently in private practice in
Washington.
</TEXT>
