<HEADLINE>
FT  06 AUG 94 / Property: Name on the wall - Cadogan's Place
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GERALD CADOGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Our competition (Weekend FT, July 9/10) for the best suggestion for a new
blue plaque to commemorate a famous person who had lived or stayed in London
produced intriguing suggestions. We had to exclude 6 Roland Gardens, SW7,
where Ninette de Valois, founder of the Royal Ballet, opened her first
school in 1926 since Dame Ninette is still alive. But it is one to pass on
to English Heritage.
James C Currey of Dallas, Texas, had an unusual proposal: the legation of
the Republic of Texas, 1838-1846, in St James's Street, SW1. Two years after
the state won independence from Mexico it sent a minister to London. The
British government proposed dominion status, as Canada obtained in 1867, but
in 1846 Texas joined the Union.
Antoin Daltun, of Dublin, suggested two sites connected to the Anglo-Irish
Treaty negotiations of 1921, which led to the Irish Free State: 22 Hans
Place, SW1, the Irish delegation's headquarters, and 15 Cadogan Gardens,
SW3, where Michael Collins stayed. Both good ideas, and unusual locations.
Thomas Hackett, in Luxembourg, wants to celebrate 90 years of the entente
cordiale with France by honouring the philosopher-poet Paul Valery, who
worked at 15 St Swithin's Lane, EC4 in 1896.
Among other suggestions was the former home of Wallis Simpson (later Duchess
of Windsor).
But the winner of the bottle of Laurent Perrier champagne must be the writer
Peter Hopkirk, who points out that John Buchan (later Lord Tweedsmuir and
Governor- General of Canada) is a surprising omission. He lived at 76
Portland Place, W1, from 1912 to 1919 where he wrote The Thirty-Nine Steps
and Greenmantle. Across the road is the Turkish ambassador's handsome
residence - 'fittingly, perhaps, as much of the action of Greenmantle is set
in Turkey'.
</TEXT>
