<HEADLINE>
FT  06 AUG 94 / Finance and the Family: Directors' transactions
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The week started very quietly with few transactions being reported. Where
there has been dealing, the bias remains towards buying, with two companies
having open offers. Directors at both Computer People and EFT Group took the
opportunity afforded by the new stock to increase their existing holdings.
Largest sale of the week was at Camellia Group, the agriculture and
financial service provision company. David Bacon, managing director, sold
5,000 shares at Pounds 25.50p. The sale accounted for over 5 per cent of his
holding, leaving him with 89,000 shares. Shortly before the closed period at
the end of March another director, Donald Green, a non-executive, also sold
stock.
Asprey, the jewellers, featured recently when John Asprey, the chairman,
sold 375,000 shares at 306p. His total stake accounts for 50 per cent of the
company so relatively the sale was not significant. This time Timothy
Cooper, who manages the Bond Street branch of operations, exercised 35,740
options and then sold them all. The company is anticipated to show pre-tax
profits growth of 18 per cent over the next year. Relatively, the share
price is underperforming the market.
Filofax, the personal organiser people, has also featured on this list
before. Richard Koch, the non-executive holder of over 2m shares - 8 per
cent - of the company, continues buying with two separate purchases of
10,000 shares at 186p and 30,000 shares at 203p.
