<HEADLINE>
FT  06 AUG 94 / World Stock Markets (Asia Pacific): Rise in bond prices
pressures the Nikkei
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMIKO TERAZONO
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A rise in bond prices to a 14-month high prompted worries over fund
allocation by institutional investors, and share prices lost ground as
dealers adjusted their positions and individuals took profits, writes Emiko
Terazono in Tokyo.
The Nikkei 225 fell 155.14 to 20,521.70 after a high of 20,680.94 and a low
of 20,467.49.
Domestic institutions had buying orders just below the 20,500 level,
preventing a sharp slide in prices, but traders also noted sell orders
around 20,700.
Volume totalled 269m shares, against 270m. Arbitrage buying and purchases by
overseas investors supported low-priced issues, but share prices declined on
small lot selling by dealers.
Traders were also worried that the rise in the yield on the 10-year
benchmark bond above 4.6 per cent would attract some institutional investors
from the equity market.
The Topix index of all first section stocks fell 6.78 to 1,649.74, while the
Nikkei 300 sank 1.30 to 299.44. Losers led gainers by 659 to 317 with 193
unchanged and, in London, the ISE/Nikkei 50 index rose 2.04 to 1,336.87.
Profit-taking depressed electrical stocks and Hitachi fell Y20 to Y1,000;
but overseas investors bought steel companies and Nippon Steel, the most
active issue of the day, rose Y2 to Y363. NKK advanced Y5 to Y279.
Ricoh, the office automation equipment maker, jumped Y26 to Y960. Investors
were encouraged by the Yamaichi Research Institute's first ever top rating
of 1 for the company, which has been cutting costs through restructuring
measures.
DDI, the telecommunications company, saw active demand following its
ten-for-one stock split. The issue rose an effective Y62,000 to Y991,000.
In Osaka, the OSE average fell 88.59 to 22,922.67 in volume of 72.2m shares.
Roundup
Fears of a further rise in US interest rates weighed on a number of the
region's markets.
HONG KONG fell back as investors took profits on a number of blue-chip
stocks following renewed fears of a rise in US interest rates.
The Hang Seng index lost 40.64 to 9,602.21, but up from an intraday low of
9,562.41. The market rose 1.3 per cent last week.
Brokers said that local and foreign investors engaged in selective selling
to hedge positions ahead of the weekend and Friday's US jobs data.
SHANGHAI's domestic market saw another substantial rise with the A index
rising 22 per cent to 700.58. Its gain on the week was 108 per cent.
By contrast the B index added 2.5 per cent to 74.40.
Turnover was Yn10.49bn.
SINGAPORE rose slightly on expectations of good second quarter economic
growth data due to be announced next week.
The Straits Times Industrials index rose 1.95 to 2,273.12, a 3 per cent
improvement on the week.
Turnover rose to SDollars 531.6m from SDollars 487.2m.
TAIPEI rose 1.9 per cent on the day on strong buying in the electronic and
plastic sectors.
The weighted index put on 129.64 to 6,919.21, 2.5 per cent on the week.
Turnover soared to TDollars 123.2bn from Thursday's TDollars 85.3bn.
SEOUL rose as investors renewed their interest in selective blue chips,
shares with low price/earnings ratios and some banking issues.
The composite stock index added 8.33 to 935.82, off a day's high of 943.48,
and up 0.2 per cent on the week.
KUALA LUMPUR improved as speculative stocks soared in the afternoon, led by
Idris Hydraulic which added 45 cents to MDollars 5.55.
Analysts said that optimism was fuelled by hopes for an announcement of an
early general election.
The composite index added 2.35 to 1,089.15, for a 6 per cent advance on the
week.
SYDNEY saw bargain hunting of blue chips push the market to a higher close
in spite of a sharp fall on Wall Street overnight. BHP climbed 10 cents to a
record close of ADollars 19.60: it is expected to rise further next week
amid buying enthusiasm related to the expansion of key projects.
The All Ordinaries index finished 8.4 stronger at 2,091.9, up 1.5 per cent
on the week.
