<HEADLINE>
FT  06 AUG 94 / International Capital Markets: Tokyo SE may ease listings
rules
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMIKO TERAZONO
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Tokyo stock exchange, facing a sharp decline in listings of overseas
companies, is considering measures to revive trading on its stagnant foreign
section.
Exchange officials are planning to ease the TSE's asset guidelines which
limit listings of overseas corporations on its foreign section to large blue
chip companies. They hope to increase listings of more south-east Asian and
Chinese companies, with growth potential, which are looking for funding
options in overseas capital markets.
The exchange plans to scrap the Y100bn net asset requirement for companies
wishing to list, and the guideline where companies must report annual
profits of at least Y20bn during the three years before the listing.
The move comes as TSE has seen an exodus of US and European companies over
the past few years due to the rise in costs stemming from the yen's
appreciation and the sharp fall in trading volumes of foreign stocks.
The number of companies listed on the TSE's foreign section has fallen to 97
from 125 in the peak in 1991.
Companies including Eastman Kodak and Chase Manhattan are among those which
have delisted, shunning the costs of Y20m to Y30m a year to maintain its
status on the TSE.
</TEXT>
