<HEADLINE>
FT  06 AUG 94 / International Company News: USAir turns down pilots'
proposals
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
USAir, the struggling US carrier in which British Airways holds a minority
stake, yesterday rejected a proposal from the pilots' union that employees
should swap Dollars 2.5bn worth of wage cuts for 25 per cent of the
company's shares.
It said the savings flowing from the plan were 'illusory' and several
serious flaws would have to be corrected before 'meaningful' negotiations
over cost reductions could take place.
However, USAir said some aspects of the pilots' proposal were encouraging,
and it was prepared to accept the principle of an equity-for-concessions
swap.
'It's a starting point,' the company said.
USAir, which faces tough competition from low-cost carriers making in-roads
into its markets, has not made a profit since 1988.
In June it put forward a plan to slash operating costs by Dollars 1bn a
year, with half of the savings coming from the wage bill.
Last week the Air Line Pilots Association proposed that employees should
yield Dollars 2.5bn worth of wage cuts over the next five years in exchange
for partial employee ownership and representation on the company's board.
</TEXT>
