FT  06 AUG 94 / UK Company News: Clarkson may incur Pounds 2m charge
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Horace Clarkson, the shipping and insurance broking group, is likely to
incur a Pounds 2.2m charge in goodwill costs linked to the disposal of its
Lloyd's Names business, writes Andrew Jack.
Its Horace Holman subsidiary was transferring future work on Estate
Protection Plan, a scheme to close off liabilities on open years for Names
who have died, to Centrewrite, a Lloyd's-controlled vehicle. Clarkson has
also handed over administration of personal stop loss policies arranged by
Holman Wade and Carritt &amp; Partners to IRISC London without any payment.
Goodwill which had previously been written off against reserves was likely
to be reinstated as a charge in the P&amp;L account for the current year.
'This is part of the nationalisation of the relationship with Names. It is
natural and evolutionary,' said Mr Robert Ward, finance director.
