<HEADLINE>
FT  06 AUG 94 / Nato jets strike at Bosnian Serbs: More attacks threatened
over seizure of weapons
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MATTHEW KAMINSKI and JEREMY KAHN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Nato jets launched an attack in Bosnia yesterday and threatened more strikes
after Serb troops seized a tank and other weapons under United Nations
control, violating the Sarajevo security zone.
The Nato attack by 14 jets was the first since April and highlights the
increasing pressure on the Bosnian Serbs, who have been left isolated this
week by their refusal to endorse an international peace plan for the region.
Lt Gen Sir Michael Rose, the UN commander in Bosnia, called for the strike
after Bosnian Serb forces ignored threats that they faced an attack if they
violated a heavy weapon exclusionary zone around the capital. He said the
only target hit was a Serb armoured vehicle fitted with a heavy 76mm gun,
known as a tank buster. He warned that if the Serbs did not return the heavy
weapons as they had promised, more air attacks would be launched against
them.
'At 18:32 (16:32 GMT) Nato aircraft engaged a target of the Bosnian Serb
army that was in violation of the total exclusion zone around Sarajevo. The
target was a tank buster that was engaged by cannon and we think destroyed,'
Gen Rose said.
British, American, Dutch and French aircraft, based at Gioia Colle in
southern Italy, took part in the raid on four targets, but all bar two US
jets failed to engage their targets due to 'weather and other difficulties'.
The raid comes a day after Serbia itself cut links with the self-declared
Bosnian Serb state. Telephone links and border traffic between the two Serb
neighbours were closed yesterday, further isolating the Bosnian Serb
leadership in Pale.
In April, allied planes bombed Serb targets in the UN-designated safe area
around Gorazde in eastern Bosnia. Since then, Bosnian Serbs have fired on UN
troops and ignored warnings to stay away from exclusionary zones.
The UN hesitated to retaliate in the hope of fashioning a peace agreement,
but Bosnian Serb leaders on Wednesday rejected a western-brokered peace deal
that would partition Bosnia-Hercegovina almost equally between Serbs and the
Croat-Moslem coalition.
Early yesterday, a T-55 tank, anti-aircraft gun and two armoured personnel
carriers were taken in a raid on a UN weapons collections point in Ilidza, a
suburb of Sarajevo.
Mr Fred Eckart, UN spokesman in New York, said the attack was justified by
the weapons seizure and the subsequent shooting at a French helicopter sent
to retrieve the equipment.
After the attack, UN officials said Bosnian Serbs had indicated they would
return all weapons taken from the UN store. The Serb officials were said to
have regretted taking the equipment.
Nato has more than 100 aircraft based in Italy, from where past strikes have
been launched. The planes enforce an international ban on military flights
over Bosnia and offer support to UN peacekeepers on the ground.
Milosevic blocks traffic to Bosnia, Page 2
</TEXT>
