<HEADLINE>
FT  06 AUG 94 / Abiola rejects terms of release
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL ADAMS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LAGOS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Nigeria's detained opposition leader Chief Moshood Abiola last night
rejected the terms of the military government's offer to release him.
In a move designed to ease the country's acute political and economic
crisis, the authorities had sanctioned the intervention of a high court
judge. The judge, in an emergency session in the capital, Abuja, granted
bail to Chief Abiola on condition that he agreed not to address political
rallies, kept the peace and did not travel out of the country without
authority.
Chief Abiola, held in Abuja on a treason charge, was the undeclared winner
of last year's annulled presidential election. He was not present at the
hearing, but a spokesman for him said he had refused to accept the terms.
The government action followed a month of mounting pressure which saw Lagos,
the biggest city, paralysed, and vital oil exports severely hit by a
continuing industry strike. Unofficial estimates put the loss of crude oil
production at over a quarter of the normal 2m barrels a day. Anglo-Dutch
Shell, which produces half of Nigeria's oil, has cut its production by at
least 400,000 barrels per day.
On Friday it suspended supplies of its Bonny medium crude oil, produced in
the Niger delta at onshore fields exposed to vio-lence and sabotage which
have been either threatened or carried out against strike-breaking.
Oil prices fell sharply on news of the release offer. The key September
Brent futures contract on the International Petroleum Exchange fell to
Dollars 17.85 in late afternoon trading in London, down 57 cents a barrel
from the previous day's close.
A national strike, which began last week but was called off on Thursday to
allow behind the scenes negotiations on Chief Abiola's release, was due to
resume on Monday. This now seems likely to go ahead, with Chief Abiola and
his supporters pressing his claim to the presidency, adding to the country's
economic difficulties and raising tensions.
Although Chief Abiola enjoys considerable support in and around Lagos,
heartland of the Yoruba tribe, there is powerful opposition to him from the
Hausa Fulani north and within the army itself.
Mr Adams Oshimole, deputy national president of the umbrella Nigeria Labour
Congress, had told Reuters news agency he understood that by the next
sitting of the high court, set for August 16, the government would drop the
treason charges, but military officials made no further comment last night.
Man in the News, Page 8
</TEXT>
