<HEADLINE>
FT  05 AUG 94 / (CORRECTED) Lloyd's set to hire debt collectors to chase
Names
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Correction (published 6th August 1994) appended to this article.
Lloyd's of London is poised to hire commercial debt collectors as part of a
tough new campaign to collect money from loss-making members of the
insurance market.
The move would represent a substantial stepping up of its efforts to close a
shortfall of nearly Pounds 662m owed by thousands of Names, the individuals
whose assets have traditionally supported the market.
Mr Peter Middleton, chief executive, said yesterday that Lloyd's did not
have the resources internally to collect all its debts.
He said the initiative was partly in response to complaints from Names'
organisations that some members of the insurance market were unfairly
concealing their assets to avoid making payments. At present Names either
enter 'hardship', a Lloyd's alternative to bankruptcy, or are pursued for
payment - ultimately through legal action.
A committee of the ruling council of Lloyd's has been created under the
chairmanship of Mr Bernard Bradford, who recently retired as head of
corporate recovery. Mr Philip Holden, a partner with Dibb Lupton Broomhead,
a law firm with two specialist debt collection offices, will be working with
the committee to produce recommendations for the next council meeting on
September 14.
Mr Holden said last night: 'This is not a normal debt collection situation.
I think there are things that can be done on a constructive basis that can
make life better for everybody.'
The aim is to develop ideas as well as quantifying the size of the problem,
which may cover as many as 14,000 Names.
Mr Robert Miller of the Association of Lloyd's Names, the biggest Names
group, welcomed the initiative but Mr Michael Freeman, a partner with
lawyers Epstein Grower Michael Freeman which is acting for many loss-making
Names, has complained about the idea. He said it looked as if Lloyd's was
trying to by-pass the legal system.
Lloyd's plans reforms, Page 6
Observer, Page 13
CORRECTION
The Association of Lloyd's Names welcomes efforts by the insurance market to
ensure that all Names with outstanding debts are treated equally, but does
not support the use of debt collectors, contrary to suggestions in
yesterday's FT.
</TEXT>
