<HEADLINE>
FT  05 AUG 94 / World Stock Markets (America): Dow drops awaiting jobs
figures
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANK MCGURTY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US stocks retreated yesterday ahead of economic data which may influence the
timing of the Federal Reserve's next move to tighten credit conditions,
writes Frank McGurty in New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average finished 26.87 down at 3,765.79, its lowest
level of the day. The Standard &amp; Poor's 500 was off 3.05 at 458.40. Trading
volume on the Big Board amounted to 294m shares. The Nasdaq composite
receded 3.51 to 720.18.
The session opened on a sour note. Investors were greeted by a piece of
economic data which did not bode well for this morning's crucial July
employment data. The Labor Department said that initial claims for
unemployment benefit had declined by 10,000 last week, suggesting that the
economy was moving along at a steady pace.
The market was counting on seeing the opposite trend in today's report.
Non-farm payrolls in July were expected to show a moderate increase of
200,000 after a sharp rise in June. If the figure came in line with
expectations, the Fed might have sufficient cause to delay its next move to
lift short-term interest rates.
Investors held their jitters in check for most of the session, but the
erosion in share prices grew more pronounced near the end of the day.
Early on, motor vehicle shares were marked down in reaction to weak July
sales data released the previous session. General Motors dropped Dollars 2
1/8 to Dollars 50 3/8 , Ford Dollars 2 to Dollars 29 1/2 and Chrysler
Dollars 1 5/8 to Dollars 45 3/4 , with Merrill Lynch lowering its ratings on
the group.
The securities house also downgraded several of their component suppliers.
As a consequence, Eaton lost Dollars 2 1/8 at Dollars 49 3/4 and Dana
Dollars 2 1/8 at Dollars 27.
Outside the motor vehicle sector, investors were initially reluctant to make
any big moves, but several large cyclical stocks fell sharply in the final
hour. International Paper gave back Dollars 1 1/8 to Dollars 75, General
Electric Dollars 1 to Dollars 48 1/2 and Caterpillar Dollars 1 to Dollars
107 5/8 .
The release of July sales data by leading retailers failed to generate much
enthusiasm or concern, even though most stores showed continued sales
improvement. Sears Roebuck slipped Dollars  7/8 to Dollars 47 1/4 and Gap
Stores declined Dollars  3/4 to Dollars 37 7/8 .
But two electronics retailers were rewarded for their strong sales
performances. Best Buy jumped Dollars 3 1/4 to Dollars 27 1/4 and Circuit
City gained Dollars 1 3/8 at Dollars 22 1/2 .
Conrail shed Dollars 1 1/4 to Dollars 55 and Norfolk Southern receded
Dollars  1/2 to Dollars 63 1/8 after a report that the two railways were
discussing a merger.
In their initial day of trading, Shandong Hueneng Power Development ADRs
finished unchanged at Dollars 14 1/4 on heavy volume of nearly 14m shares.
The company is the first Chinese enterprise with a primary listing on the
NYSE.
Canada
Toronto closed on a mixed note after moderate trading. The TSE 300 index
lost 3.96 points at 4,202.09, but advances outscored declines by 380 to 345.
Volume was 53.7m shares.
Seven of the 14 sub-indices rose, led by real estate, up 1.5 per cent. The
conglomerates group gained 1.2 per cent as Canadian Pacific put on C 3/8 at
CDollars 22 1/2 in the wake of impressive second-quarter financial results
announced earlier in the week. Financial services fell 1.3 per cent.
Mexico
Profit-taking after four straight days of gains brought the market down
initially, but demand from foreign investors left a slightly higher finish
on balance. The IPC index of 37 leading shares was finally 6.50, or 0.25 per
cent, up at 2,573.81. Turnover was a moderate 1.33bn new pesos on 109.3m
shares traded.
Supporting the market was news that Mexico's industrial production grew 3.1
per cent in May, the second highest monthly increase of the year.
The index has gained 362 points, or 16.4 per cent, since July 20, helped by
better than expected second-quarter company reports and investor confidence
in a victory by the ruling party in the August 21 presidential elections.
</TEXT>
