<PROFILE>_AN-EHEC9AEUFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940805
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  05 AUG 94 / Markets Report: Dollar awaits job news
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The US dollar spent much of the day trading in a narrow range against the
yen and the D-Mark, as the markets awaited what are seen as crucial non-farm
payroll figures today, writes Philip Coggan.
Analysts said the employment data will give the markets a crucial indication
as to whether the Federal Open Market Committee is likely to increase
interest rates at its next meeting on August 16.
Meanwhile, the Italian lira consolidated its recent gains against the
D-Mark. The Italian Senate formally approved the government's financial
programme for the next three years, and the lira gained from the perception
that, with the holiday period about to start, political worries would
subside for another month.
The Bank of Portugal followed up the Bank of Spain's 15 basis-point cut in
its key money market rates on Wednesday.
The Portuguese lowered the regular money market rate for draining funds from
10.5 per cent to 9.75 per cent, and the emergency lending rate from 13 per
cent to 12.5 per cent. The escudo firmed slightly against the D-Mark to
Es101.9 from Wednesday's Es102.1.
The dollar spent much of the day hovering around the Y100 mark, closing in
London at Y100.2 from Y100.175 on Wednesday night. Against the D-Mark, the
dollar edged up to DM1.581, from the previous London close of DM1.5792. In
New York it finished at Y100.475 and DM1.5872.
Trading was thin, with markets showing evidence of having entered a holiday
lull. The US currency did receive a brief boost during the day, on rumours,
later denied, that the superpower had invaded Haiti.
Figures for jobless claims, which fell to 319,000, from 329,000 in the
previous week, were largely ignored, as these numbers are seen as more
erratic than today's non-farm payroll statistics.
According to Mr Ian Gunner, international economist at Chase Manhattan Bank:
'Some in the market are beginning to question whether the Fed will tighten
after August 16, or will wait for the following meeting in September.'
The outlook for the dollar is complicated by its recent close relationship
with the Treasury bond markets. Strong payroll numbers, while making a Fed
tightening more likely, will hit the T-bond market. Conversely, weak payroll
numbers will make the Fed's recent slowness to raise rates more credible,
and will boost T-bonds.
Economists polled by Reuters are forecasting a rise in the non-farm payroll
of 200,000 in July, well down from the 379,000 increase seen in June, a
figure boosted by the World Cup football tournament.
Meanwhile, evidence of the strength of the German economy emerged yesterday
with buoyant manufacturing orders and a fall in seasonally adjusted
unemployment to 2.575m in July from 2.593m in June.
After the Senate's passing of the finance package, the lira finished the day
in London at L997.9/DM, having closed at L998.8/DM on Wednesday. Mr Jeremy
Hawkins, senior economic adviser at Bank of America, said: 'There will be a
quiet period on the political front with parliament going into recess. Some
of the potential negatives have been laid to rest for the time being.'
According to Mr Robert Thomas, director and head of research at NatWest
Capital Markets, events of the last few days mean that Mr Silvio Berlusconi
(Italy's prime minister) is now going to be under less pressure. Mr Ian
Gunner of Chase Manhattan thinks the lira is now likely to trade in the
L990-L1,008 range for the near future.
But Mr Neil MacKinnon, chief economist at Citibank in Europe, said: 'There
are still question marks over the shelf life of the Berlusconi
administration. The lira is by no means out of the woods.'
Having traded in a narrow range around DM2.4250 during the morning, sterling
regained a little more of its June losses against the D-Mark, closing at
DM2.4333, up from DM2.4317.
Against the dollar, the pound weakened slightly to Dollars 1.5391, from
Wednesday's close of Dollars 1.5399. Sterling's effective index ended at
79.3, unchanged from Wednesday's finish, but up from the opening of 79.1.
However, Mr MacKinnon said he had the impression that 'most international
investors still consider sterling to be in a long term downtrend'.
In the money markets, the Bank of England gave an initial Pounds 900m of
assistance, adding further tranches of Pounds 250m, Pounds 62m and Pounds
165m later in the day to alleviate a shortage which was gradually revised up
from Pounds 1.15bn to Pounds 1.35bn. Overnight rates traded in the range of
5 1/4 to 4 1/4 per cent.
Although expectations of an imminent base rate rise have receded this week
with the publication of the Bank's quarterly inflation report, short
sterling edged down a further 5 basis points yesterday, and still implies an
increase to 5.75 per cent before September 21.
Mr Avinash Persaud, head of currency strategy at JP Morgan in Europe, said:
'Market expectations are extremely fragile.' Last week's base rate
speculation was started by a Treasury bill auction and another auction is
due today.
</TEXT>
