<HEADLINE>
FT  05 AUG 94 / Government Bonds: European prices slip ahead of US jobs data
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CONNER MIDDELMANN and FRANK MCGURTY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Stronger-than-expected economic data in Germany and position-squaring ahead
of today's US jobs report put downward pressure on prices in most European
government bond markets yesterday.
German government bonds slipped more than  1/2 point following a
larger-than-forecast jump in June manufacturing orders and the second
consecutive drop in seasonally-adjusted jobless figures.
The data were taken to indicate that the German recovery is stronger than
widely assumed, causing some market participants to revise their projections
for short-term interest rates.
This took a particularly heavy toll on the short end of the market, where
some 1995 three-month Euromark interest rate contracts fell by up to a
quarter-point.
But the long end also suffered, with the September bund future on Liffe
falling by around 0.54 point to 93.55.
French government issues followed bunds lower, but were further pressed by
the tepid reception to the Treasury's latest auction of long-dated bonds.
This caused French bonds to underperform their German counterparts, their
10-year yield spread over bunds widening to 46 basis points from 40 basis
points on Wednesday.
The auction yielded a bid-to-cover ratio of 2.09 on FFr13.4bn of 10-year
bonds, 2.02 times on FFr2.95bn of 14-year paper 1.82 times on FFr3.6bn of
30-year bonds.
When the September notional bond future on Matif approached technical
support at 117.40, retail selling kicked in, pushing the contract even
lower, he said. It closed at 117.08, down 0.82 point on the day.
UK gilts followed continental European markets lower, pressed further by
sales ahead of today's data releases in the US and the UK.
'The market had got a bit too long on the relief that there was no rate
rise, and some people were squaring their positions ahead of the US jobs
numbers and UK industrial production and manufacturing output data,' said Mr
Ifty Islam, fixed income strategist at Merrill Lynch.
Gilts underperformed bunds, with the 10-year yield spread widening by around
10 basis points to 175 basis points. The September long gilt future fell one
point to 102 3/16 .
US Treasury bonds drifted lower yesterday as dealers squared their positions
ahead of today's crucial data on July employment.
Late in the session, the benchmark 30-year government bond was  9/32 lower
at 86 3/32 , with the yield rising to 7.412 per cent. At the short end, the
two-year note was off  1/16 at 100 9/32 , to yield 5.955 per cent.
Yesterday's session brought a piece of negative news as the market prepared
for this morning's jobs report. The government announced that initial claims
for unemployment benefit had declined by 10,000 last week, suggesting the
economy was moving along at a steady pace.
The reading was unfavourable to a market looking for signs of moderating
growth, which could delay the Federal Reserve's next move to lift short-term
interest rates. Bond prices slipped on the announcement, but the declines
were modest.
Still, traders were hoping the figure was not a preview of today's data on
non-farm payrolls. An increase of more than 200,000 jobs could send bonds
prices sharply lower.
Yesterday, a neutral scenario seemed to be holding sway. Most investors
appeared confident the payroll figure would come in near expectations. But
the approach of next week's quarterly refunding operation, which would bring
a big influx of supply into the market, could stand an obstacle to any
upswing in bonds prices even if today's data proved supportive.
</TEXT>
