<HEADLINE>
FT  05 AUG 94 / International Company News: QVC undecided on bid from
shareholders
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The board of QVC Network, the US cable television shopping group, was still
locked in discussions last night over whether to accept a takeover offer
from its two largest shareholders, Comcast Communications and Liberty Media.
The cable companies are reported to have increased their original offer for
the 65 per cent of QVC that they do not already own from Dollars 44 a share
to Dollars 46 a share, an all-cash bid which values QVC at just under
Dollars 1.5bn.
Although QVC was expected to accept the revised offer yesterday, the lack of
an early announcement from the board meeting, which started at 10.30am in
New York, led some analysts to suggest that there may have been last-minute
opposition to the deal from some members - possibly from Mr Barry Diller,
QVC chairman, who is believed to have wanted the company to wait and see if
a higher bid would emerge from another source.
A QVC spokesman declined to comment on the progress of the board meeting,
but last night sources close to the company said the board was still hoping
to announce an agreement within a few hours.
Last month the QVC board was close to accepting a merger offer from the CBS
television broadcasting network, but before it could sanction the deal
Comcast stepped in with a higher bid on July 12. Ten days later, Comcast was
joined by Liberty Media.
</TEXT>
