<HEADLINE>
FT  05 AUG 94 / Kidder Peabody investigation blames Jett for false profits
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Kidder Peabody yesterday tried again to put an end to the bond trading
scandal which has dogged it since April by publishing an investigation it
commissioned into the affair.
The report pins the blame on Mr Joseph Jett, the government bond trader who
Kidder has claimed created Dollars 350m (Pounds 226m) of fictitious profits
in its government bond trading business in order to boost his own
performance bonus.
It adds that 'lax oversight, as well as poor judgments and missed
opportunities' on the part of Kidder executives meant that Mr Jett's false
profits were not identified for more than two years.
Mr Jett's lawyer, Mr Kenneth Warner, called the report 'predictably
one-sided and incomplete', and said his client would be vindicated 'when a
truly independent investigation is completed'.
Mr Jett's sacking in April prompted widespread concern on Wall Street about
Kidder's financial health, and led General Electric, its parent, to issue a
series of statements of support for the firm. The fall-out led eventually to
the departure of Mr Michael Carpenter, Kidder's chief executive.
Mr Edward Cerullo, head of Kidder's fixed income division, also left in
recent weeks. According to yesterday's report, Mr Cerullo's supervision of
Mr Jett was 'seriously deficient', though it adds: 'It is clear that he and
Jett were not co-conspirators.'
Kidder said yesterday it had also sacked Mr Melvin Mullin, who was directly
responsible for supervising Mr Jett until February 1993.
The investigation was carried out by Mr Gary Lynch, who as head of the
Securities and Exchange Commission's enforcement division in the 1980s
pursued Mr Michael Milken and Mr Ivan Boesky, both of whom were later
convicted.
Mr Jett has claimed that the disputed trades were carried out at the request
of his superiors, and were intended to put a gloss on Kidder's financial
position by removing securities from its balance sheet. His trades are
understood to have been the subject of investigation by a number of
authorities since April, though no charges have been brought.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Kidder Peabody Group Inc.
</CO>
<XX>
